  "prompt": "What does the Bible say about psychology?",
  "response": "The Bible does not directly discuss modern psychology as we understand it today, since psychology as a scientific discipline did not exist during biblical times. However, the Bible does offer insights into human behavior, emotions, mental health, and relationships that have some parallels with psychological principles:\n\n1. Human Nature\n- Recognizes human complexity (Jeremiah 17:9)\n- Acknowledges internal struggles and conflicting desires (Romans 7:15-20)\n\n2. Mental/Emotional Health\n- Addresses emotional challenges like grief, anxiety, depression\n- Encourages seeking counsel (Proverbs 15:22)\n- Promotes emotional healing and wholeness\n\n3. Relationships\n- Emphasizes love, forgiveness, empathy\n- Provides guidance on conflict resolution\n- Teaches about healthy communication\n\n4. Coping Mechanisms\n- Encourages prayer and faith as means of dealing with stress\n- Promotes hope and resilience\n- Teaches about peace and contentment\n\n5. Self-Understanding\n- Encourages self-reflection\n- Promotes personal growth and transformation\n- Emphasizes understanding one's identity\n\nWhile not a psychology textbook, the Bible offers spiritual and philosophical insights into human behavior and mental processes that can complement professional psychological understanding.\n\nMany Christian counselors integrate biblical principles with psychological research in their therapeutic approaches.",
